Subject: [PATCH 3/6] feat: add language-agnostic code quality framework
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Three components:

1. biome.json — TypeScript/JS quality config for the harness itself
   Rules: noExplicitAny, noConsole, noImportCycles, noFloatingPromises,
   noUnusedImports, noDebugger, useImportType, organizeImports, etc.
   Baseline: 282 files, 490 errors, 1415 warnings (to be fixed incrementally).

2. code-quality/ — language-agnostic detection and enforcement extension
   - registry.ts: maps 17 languages to their fmt/lint/vet/test tools
     (TypeScript→Biome, Go→gofmt+golangci-lint, Rust→rustfmt+clippy,
      Python→ruff+mypy, Java, Kotlin, C/C++, C#, Ruby, PHP, Swift,
      Elixir, Zig, Shell, SQL, Terraform, Dockerfile)
   - detect.ts: scans any codebase, counts files by extension,
     finds manifest files, checks which tools are installed vs missing
   - index.ts: extension that runs detection on session_start,
     provides /quality command (scan|fix|setup|report)

3. docs/CODE_QUALITY_STANDARD.md — universal rules for all agents
   - The workflow: detect stack → install tools → run on every write
   - Tool table for every language (formatter + linter + typechecker)
   - 19 anti-patterns every agent must avoid (imports, errors, types,
     architecture, async)
   - Per-role instructions (planner, worker, tester, reviewer, etc.)

The key insight: the harness generates code in ANY language, not just
TypeScript. Biome is right for TS but useless for Go/Rust/Python.
The registry knows what tool to use for each language. The detector
figures out what language a codebase uses. The standard tells agents
what rules to follow regardless of language.
